06049nam a22008055i 9780292735330DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212011txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011019055  a97802927353307 a10.7560/7266282doi  a(DE-B1597)586751  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aPN1995.9.H6bH64 2011 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.4361640900aHorror after 9/11 :bWorld of Fear, Cinema of Terror /ced. by Sam J. Miller, Aviva Briefel. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (273 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. Why Horror? -- t1. Black Screens, Lost Bodies: The Cinematic Apparatus of 9/11 Horror -- t2. Let’s Roll: Hollywood Takes on 9/11 -- t3. Transforming Horror: David Cronenberg’s Cinematic Gestures after 9/11 -- tPart Two. Horror Looks at Itself -- t4. Caught on Tape? The Politics of Video in the New Torture Film -- t5. Cutting into Concepts of “Reflectionist” Cinema? The Saw Franchise and Puzzles of Post- 9/11 Horror -- t6. The Host versus Cloverfield -- t7. “Shop ’Til You Drop!”: Consumerism and Horror -- tPart Three. Horror in Action -- t8. Historicizing the Bush Years: Politics, Horror Film, and Francis Lawrence’s I Am Legend -- t9. “I Am the Devil and I’m Here to Do the Devil’s Work”: Rob Zombie, George W. Bush, and the Limits of American Freedom -- t10. “Forever Family” Values: Twilight and the Modern Mormon Vampire -- t11. Assimilation and the Queer Monster -- tSelected Bibliography -- tSelected Filmography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHorror films have exploded in popularity since the tragic events of September 11, 2001, many of them breaking box-office records and generating broad public discourse. These films have attracted A-list talent and earned award nods, while at the same time becoming darker, more disturbing, and increasingly apocalyptic. Why has horror suddenly become more popular, and what does this say about us? What do specific horror films and trends convey about American society in the wake of events so horrific that many pundits initially predicted the death of the genre? How could American audiences, after tasting real horror, want to consume images of violence on screen? Horror after 9/11 represents the first major exploration of the horror genre through the lens of 9/11 and the subsequent transformation of American and global society. Films discussed include the Twilight saga; the Saw series; Hostel; Cloverfield; 28 Days Later; remakes of The Texas Chainsaw Massacre, Dawn of the Dead, and The Hills Have Eyes; and many more. The contributors analyze recent trends in the horror genre, including the rise of 'torture porn,' the big-budget remakes of classic horror films, the reinvention of traditional monsters such as vampires and zombies, and a new awareness of visual technologies as sites of horror in themselves. The essays examine the allegorical role that the horror film has held in the last ten years, and the ways that it has been translating and reinterpreting the discourses and images of terror into its own cinematic language.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHorror filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aSeptember 11 Terrorist Attacks, 2001xInfluence. 0aTerror in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aBenshoff, Harry M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlake, Linnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBriefel, Aviva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBriefel, Aviva, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabul